{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656661"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:17:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:17:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18758"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18758"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.2,0.2,0.15,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79458"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11490"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18758"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10489"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26596"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27182"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79458"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe glomerular filtration rate depends on several pressures within the glomerular capillaries and Bowman\u0027s space. One of these pressures provides the main driving force for filtration.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best represents the normal glomerular hydrostatic pressure in humans?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["15 mmHg","25 mmHg","35 mmHg","45 mmHg","55 mmHg"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe normal \u003Cstrong\u003E55 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E glomerular hydrostatic pressure provides the main driving force for glomerular filtration. This relatively high pressure is maintained by the resistance differences between the afferent and efferent arterioles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E15 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - This is closer to the pressure typically found in Bowman\u0027s space\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E25 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - This is too low to overcome the opposing oncotic pressure and achieve normal filtration rates\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E35 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - This pressure would be insufficient to maintain normal glomerular filtration\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E45 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - While closer to the correct value, this pressure would result in suboptimal filtration rates\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe net filtration pressure is determined by the balance between the glomerular hydrostatic pressure (pushing fluid out) and the opposing forces of Bowman\u0027s space hydrostatic pressure and plasma oncotic pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glomerular hydrostatic pressure is approximately 55 mmHg in healthy humans.","Glomerular hydrostatic pressure is the main driving force for glomerular filtration.","Glomerular hydrostatic pressure is maintained by arteriolar tone, with the afferent arteriole having a greater influence than the efferent arteriole."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"ques